usiness. \n<br /> \n<br />Internship positions are available year-round working approximately 10-20 hours per week between the hours of 9:00 a.m. - 5:00 p.m. at the Texas Gulf Coast Office - 5433 Westheimer, Houston, TX 77056. Internships are unpaid \n<br /> \n<br />If you have any questions or concerns please contact Tiffany Valeri at tiffany.valeri@lls.org or 832.463.3626. \n<br />','Special Events Intern, Light The Night Walks, Texas Gulf Coast Chapter','','publish','closed','closed','','special-events-intern-light-the-night-walks-texas-gulf-coast-chapter','','','2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','',0,'http://ec2-184-73-133-229.compute-1.amazonaws.com/?p=1602',0,'noo_job','',0),(1603,30,'1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society','The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society','','publish','closed','closed','','the-leukemialymphoma-society','','','1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','',0,'',0,'noo_company','',0),(1604,30,'2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','<h2>Description</h2> UIA (Uzan International Artists) is a leading Artist Management firm in New York City that represents a diverse roster of entertainers, creative professionals, and productions. We have a subsidiary company which serves as the booking arm of our corporation called UIA Presents. We are seeking an Artist Management/Booking Representative Intern who will be responsible for administrative support, IT support, and Marketing/PR/Social Media support. The Artist Management/Booking Representative Intern will work directly with the Artist Management team to support firm operations and, in limited instances, work directly with clients on logistics and marketing tasks. Should be available 32-40 hours per week during business hours. Internship is unpaid. Monthly commuting expenses will be reimbursed, lunches provided or reimbursed, and frequent complimentary tickets to NYC live entertainment performances are available. We will gladly provide references or letters of recommendation.<h3>Responsibilities</h3> - Execute administrative office functions (filing, copying, and phone support). \n<br />- Perform content updates to company website. \n<br />- Perform updates to company social media platforms and find ways to engage with social media audience. \n<br />- Assist in developing and contributing to public relations and marketing activities largely related to social media and internet marketing. \n<br />- Interact with internal departments to carry out client requirements. \n<br />- Complete special projects and reports as delegated by artist management team to streamline operations. \n<br />- Assist with routing/touring dates for our acts/artists \n<br />-Assist with contracts \n<br />-Researching new contacts/venues to pitch our acts/artists<h2>Requirements</h2> - Excellent communication skills, grammar, and the ability to communicate via written, oral and visual media. \n<br />- An innovative self-starter with problem solving skills, creativity, ambition, and a strong work ethic. \n<br />- Strong knowledge of Microsoft Windows, Microsoft Office, and Adobe Creative Suite products, with the ability to troubleshoot and solve technical problems and provide first level tech support to office staff. \n<br />- Keen administrative skills and knowledge of standard administrative office practices. \n<br />- Passion for social media, knowledge of Facebook and Twitter best practices for businesses, and the ability to interpret social media analytics and report on performance. \n<br />- The ability to see a project from start to finish with minimal supervision and intervention. \n<br />- Basic knowledge of HTML for updates to WordPress-based website. \n<br />- Incredibly personable, and enjoys interpersonal communication. \n<br />- Knowledge of theatre, musical theatre and the overall music industry are a plus \n<br />- Ability to handle and respect confidential and sensitive information. \n<br />- Should not be an active or aspiring performer.','Artist Management/Booking Representative Intern','','publish','closed','closed','','artist-managementbooking-representative-intern','','','2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','',0,'http://ec2-184-73-133-229.compute-1.amazonaws.com/?p=1604',0,'noo_job','',0),(1605,30,'1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','UIA (Uzan International Artists)','UIA (Uzan International Artists)','','publish','closed','closed','','uia-uzan-international-artists','','','1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','',0,'',0,'noo_company','',0),(1606,30,'2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','<h2>Description</h2> Camp Starfish is a not-for-profit residential summer camp that serves children between the ages of 5 to 18 who have emotional, behavioral and learning challenges. Using a combination of traditional camp programs combined with a one-to-one staff to camper ratio, we have created a camp that meets the needs of children who have not been or would not be successful at other camps. Our campers experience success and fun at our camp because of the individualized attention they receive from our talented, creative, amazing staff. \n<br /> \n<br />We’re looking for motivated and fun individuals who have a desire and ability to work with children outdoors, in a mission-focused, not-for-profit organization dedicated to fostering the success and growth of children with emotional, learning and behavioral problems by providing individualized attention as part of structured, nurturing, and fun group programs. \n<br /><h3>Responsibilities</h3> A Camp Starfish TIDES Advisor provides day-to-day guidance and mentorship to a small group of teens (Trainees) in the TIDES program. Responsibilities include ensuring Trainees create and follow their daily schedules, role modelling appropriate professional and social skills, assisting the TIDES Administrator in preparing and delivering curriculum content (subjects include nutrition, cooking, healthy lifestyle choices, professional working skills, money management, college life, and much more), balancing a “hands off” approach with independent life skill guidance to ensure all Trainees are as self-sufficient as possible. \n<br /> \n<br />All advisors live and work as part of the TIDES community. The community creates its own schedule, buys its own groceries and cooks preferred meals, operates a Farmers Market stall, and has relaxed vibe to it. You’ll definitely get the traditional summer camp experience but will have far greater freedom and offsite adventures than your standard camp counselor. For example, each week the TIDES community chooses a number of offsite group activities which include going to an amusement park, a day at the mall, hiking a mountain, a trip to Boston, a nice dinner out, movie night, and many more. \n<br /> \n<br />For more information on the TIDES program: \n<a href=\"http://campstarfish.org/camps/tides.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://campstarfish.org/camps/tides.html</a> \n<br /><h2>Requirements</h2> Successful candidates demonstrate: \n<br />• Strong personal integrity, adaptability, emotional intelligence, enthusiasm, patience, and self-control \n<br />• Able to make quick and safe decisions during offsite activities and positively represent Camp Starfish \n<br />• Ability to understand, role model, and adhere to Starfish policies and procedures \n<br />• Use of the “Starfish Tools” as a foundation for professional development and interactions \n<br />• Willingness and ability to seek and accept supervision and guidance \n<br />• Embrace and accept differences in religion/ethnicity/culture/race/gender/sexual orientation and/or other diversities. Willingness and ability to treat all campers and staff fairly regardless of identity, background, and/or preferences \n<br />• Pass all background checks as required for seasonal employees of an organization working with vulnerable child populations \n<br />• Ability to work the entirety of the season, as stated in a letter of hire, including staff training dates \n<br />• Prefer at least 19 years old with one year of college/work/life experience outside of high school \n<br /> \n<br /> \n<br />This is a residential summer camp position in New Hampshire with Summer 2018 employment dates: June 6th - August 24th. Live, work, and play with some truly amazing children.','Summer Camp Counselor: Young Adult Life Skills Advisor','','publish','closed','closed','','summer-camp-counselor-young-adult-life-skills-advisor','','','2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','',0,'http://ec2-184-73-133-229.compute-1.amazonaws.com/?p=1606',0,'noo_job','',0),(1607,30,'1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','Camp Starfish','Camp Starfish','','publish','closed','closed','','camp-starfish','','','1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','',0,'',0,'noo_company','',0),(1608,30,'2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','<h2>Description</h2> To ensure you receive a response for your application and continue receiving our emails for further communication, please add \'\'newvolunteers@savethewater.com” to your address book or safe list. \n<br /> \n<br />- This is an unpaid volunteer opportunity and Associates are expected to contribute a minimum of between 5 hours per week and be responsive to emails within two (2) calendar days. \n<br />- Associates must be willing to attend weekly/bi-weekly meetings as and when required. \n<br /> \n<br />About Us \n<br />Do you know what harmful contaminants are in your water? How it gets there? What effect it has on your families and environment? Save the Water™ (STW™) is the one looking for answers. \n<br /> \n<br />STW™ is a U.S.-based nonprofit organization whose mission is to conduct water research to identify and remove harmful contaminants in water; and to raise public awareness about water contamination and its health impacts. STW™ also offers educational programs to excite young minds about water science.Our volunteers are diverse professionals from all over the world bringing their knowledge and experience to STW™because we care deeply about our communities and water resources. \n<br /> \n<br />To learn more about Save the Water™, please visit \n<a href=\"http://www.savethewater.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">www.savethewater.org</a>. \n<br /> \n<br />ABOUT THE EDUCATION GROUP \n<br />The Education Group is part of Save the WaterTM (STW™)’s Public Awareness efforts. We design educational materials to inform concerned citizens about water contamination and what they can do to help. Our content is distributed through the STW™ website and our Day in the Life of a Scientist (DILOS™) STEM Classroom Workshop. Through education, we aim to arm our readers to be agents of environmental and social change so that we may preserve our water sources for generations to come. \n<br /> \n<br />The Role \n<br />Support the Education Group by researching and writing content that increases public awareness about water contamination.<h3>Responsibilities</h3> What you will be responsible for... \n<br />- Research topics on water contamination using credible sources. \n<br />- Catalog references and fact check sources. \n<br />- Write educational content on topics including, but not limited: \n<br />- Water Education, Sources of Contamination, Environmental Impacts, Contaminant Information \n<br />- Update content on website when needed. \n<br />- Monitor web pages for broken and error links. \n<br />- Assist Project Leader in brainstorming content for the website. \n<br />- Deliver project updates at monthly Education Group meeting \n<br /> \n<br /> \n<br />Your Take Away….. \n<br />- Chance to develop or master your professional &amp; leadership skills \n<br />- Advance &amp; improve your project management skills \n<br />- Work with a team of diverse professionals from all over the world \n<br />- Opportunity to handle multiple projects \n<br />- Be a part of a mission to save our resources and make a deep impact<h2>Requirements</h2> Apply Now if You have... \n<br />- Demonstrated ability to handle multiple projects and details simultaneously. \n<br />- Effective oral communication skills and ability to work cooperatively with staff. \n<br />- Innovative thinker who is passionate about our cause. \n<br />- Associates degree completed or equivalent work experience (6 months to 1 year full time/ paid non-profit work experience). \n<br />- Excellent content writing skills (grammar, punctuation, etc.) \n<br />- Background in STEM field (e.g. Environmental Science, Physical Sciences, Engineering, or other related field) \n<br />- Previous experience with WordPress preferred but not necessary \n<br />- Graphic design skills preferred, but not necessary \n<br />- Background in STEM education as instructor or tutor a plus \n<br />- Previous laboratory experience in academic/industrial research a plus \n<br />- Familiar with current school age trends. \n<br />- Continuous access to internet is required— as a virtual organization, we rely on multiple Google platforms (e.g. Gmail, Hangouts, Calendar, and Drive) to support our workflow and communication. \n<br />- Availability during US Eastern Time Zone is preferred \n<br /> \n<br />How to apply: \n<br />Please include a 1-2 page writing sample that exemplifies your ability to communicate an academic topic, preferably in a STEM field. This sample can be an excerpt from an essay or report. Please submit the above along with your resume to newvolunteers@savethewater.org. We would love to hear from you! \n<br /> \n<br />&copy; 2018 \n<br /> \n<br />HOW TO APPLY \n<br />newvolunteers@savethewater.org','EDUCATION ASSOCIATE, WEBSITE EDUCATION MATERIAL/RESEARCHER AND WRITER (REMOTE)','','publish','closed','closed','','education-associate-website-education-materialresearcher-and-writer-remote','','','2018-04-06 00:00:00','2018-04-06 00:00:00','',0,'http://ec2-184-73-133-229.compute-1.amazonaws.com/?p=1608',0,'noo_job','',0),(1609,30,'2018-0