0:00:00','2018-04-05 00:00:00','<h2>Description</h2> The Spanish Language Programs &amp; Outreach (SLPO) Intern plays an important role in supporting 826DC’s educational programs by engaging with Spanish-speaking students and families, and by translating and creating outreach materials. \n<br /> \n<br />SLPO Interns support all aspects of on-site and off-site programs, publishing projects, and resource and curriculum development, specifically for English Language Learners. The bulk of the internship role will be to support students between ages 6-18 with their creative and expository writing. Persons hired for this position may work one-on-one in a mentorship capacity, in small groups, or through large group instruction when working with students, depending on current programming needs at the time of the internship. \n<br /> \n<br />Candidates should have an interest or experience in education, working with children, youth development, writing and the arts in a professional and data-driven setting, nonprofits, and/or social justice work. Candidates must be comfortable working with diverse populations and with local (inside the District) travel to programming locations, as required. Interested applicants must have a working fluency in both written and spoken Spanish and English. Spanish Language Programs &amp; Outreach Interns work closely with the Programs Director and On-site Programs Manager. \n<br /> \n<br /> \n<br /><h3>Responsibilities</h3> Support the Programs Department in the execution of all 826DC on-site and off-site programming, especially as it relates to Spanish-language support, including but not limited to: After-School Tutoring, Field Trips, and In School Writing, Editing &amp; Publishing. Please note: The programs and opportunities assigned to you will largely depend on our programming needs and your internship schedule. \n<br /> \n<br />Possible program specific duties include, but are not limited to: lesson planning and implementation, workshop design and execution, student data tracking, enthusiastic storytelling, chapbook production, copyediting, translations, and supporting volunteering and store operations. \n<br /> \n<br />Adhere to 826DC’s approach to working with and supporting students of all ages through positive youth development and experiential learning; support students who participate in 826DC programming with positive reinforcement, positive engagement and redirection, and a sense of humor. \n<br /> \n<br />Support and/or create on-site and off-site writing workshops that develop student writing skills, including students with learning differences, English Language Learners, students with disabilities, and students from diverse backgrounds. Participate in required local travel to programming locations, including travel by Metro (train/bus), personal vehicle, and/or walking distances of up to 1 mile. \n<br /> \n<br />Support the research and development of programming lesson plans and curriculum. Support 826DC staff with outreach to the local community, particularly DC’s Latino community, including but not limited to communicating with parents of 826DC students and building relationships with local teachers and schools. \n<br /> \n<br />Support in the research and development of Spanish language programming and outreach sustainability documents. Support execution of 826DC’s strategic planning and programmatic growth goals. \n<br /> \n<br />Support 826DC’s volunteer operations through direct outreach and support of volunteer management systems, including our volunteer database, Salesforce. Support 826DC’s program design through accurate collection and input of student involvement data. Support 826DC external events and initiatives, as appropriate; attend, as you are able, 826DC events and volunteer socials. \n<br /> \n<br />Write appropriate and relevant content for 826DC’s blog and website, as requested. Work a regular weekly shift in the 826DC storefront, and use shift to inform visitors about 826DC and its programs. Respond to and complete in a timely manner all emails and assigned projects/tasks. \n<br /><h2>Requirements</h2> Proficiency levels: ILR Level 3 or higher in Spanish and ILR Level 4 or higher in English. \n<br /> \n<br />Interest in writing, the arts, education, nonprofits, youth development, or arts education. \n<br /> \n<br />Strong written and verbal communication skills. \n<br /> \n<br />Experience working with children in either a formal or informal setting (teaching, summer camp, workshops, tutoring, mentoring, babysitting). \n<br />','Spanish Language Programs & Outreach (SLPO) Internship','','publish','closed','closed','','spanish-language-programsoutreach-slpo-internship','','','2018-04-05 00:00:00','2018-04-05 00:00:00','',0,'http://ec2-184-73-133-229.compute-1.amazonaws.com/?p=1774',0,'noo_job','',0),(1775,30,'1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','826DC','826DC','','publish','closed','closed','','826dc','','','1970-01-01 08:00:00','1970-01-01 08:00:00','',0,'',0,'noo_company','',0),(1776,30,'2018-04-05 00:00:00','2018-04-05 00:00:00','<h2>Description</h2> Purpose: \n<br />Bright Shiny Objects is a lifestyle brand that offers services and products for women with ADHD who want to transform their lives. We are a women-with-ADHD-owned startup company looking to offer an intern a total immersion experience into a business that offers coaching, online programs, community and eventually a wide range of beauty, personal care and lifestyle products. The intern will work directly with the company founders as part of a remote, virtual team.<h3>Responsibilities</h3> - Lead the planning and implementation of projects. \n<br />- Ensure that all projects are delivered on-time, within scope and budget. \n<br />- Facilitate the definition of project scope, tasks, resource requirements and goals. \n<br />- Develop and maintain project plans, timelines and documentation. \n<br />- Coordinate internal and external resources. \n<br />- Assemble,